CpG island methylator phenotype (CIMP) classification using DNA methylation array in R

Sofie Degerman et al

15/Oct/2024

CIMP panel and classification

The CpG island methylator phenotype (CIMP) classification can be used to identify epigenetic sub-types of cancers, e.g. T-cell acute lymphoblastic leukemia.

It is currently based on Illumina methylation arrays, using the DNA methylation patterns of a panel of CpGs located in promoter regions throughout the genome. They are 1099 CpGs on the 450k and EPIC v.1 arrays, and 1073 CpGs on the EPIC v.2 arrays.

Using CIMP you can classify samples into two subgroups:

  • CIMP high, a sample with > 40% of CIMP panel CpGs presenting β-values > 0.4, and

  • CIMP low, a sample with ≤ 40% of CIMP panel CpGs presenting β-values > 0.4.

  • It is also possible to obtain a CIMP% for each sample, that is the percentage of CIMP panel CpGs with a β-value > 0.4.

Figure. Heatmap showing the CIMP CpGs panel and examplifying the CIMP classification and CIMP percentage of control samples and of T-cell leukemia samples using 450k and EPIC v.1 arrays.

The CpG Island Methylator Phenotype (CIMP) panel was first identified on the Illumina HumanMethylation 27K BeadChip (27K) array, by selecting CpGs with a β-value standard deviation greater or equal to 0.3 within the analyzed diagnostic T-ALL samples, resulting in a panel of 1347 CpGs. The CIMP classification was determined using hierarchical clustering. The cluster with the lowest methylation level was labeled as CIMP-low, while the clusters with intermediate and high methylation levels were labeled as CIMP-high (Borssén et al 2013 https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0065373). With the introduction of the Infinium HumanMethylation450 (450K) BeadChip array, the CIMP panel was updated to include only CpGs present on both arrays (1303 of the 1347 original CpGs), and the panel was filtered for multimapping CpGs and CpGs within 3 base pairs from an single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) (Nordlund et al 2013 https://doi.org/10.1186/gb-2013-14-9-r105), leaving 1293 CpGs for the 450K CIMP panel. Furthermore, by analyzing the empirical cumulative distribution function, we selected a new classification criterion for CIMP that best aligns with hierarchical clusters. This strategy allows CIMP classification of single samples. Samples with more than 40% of CpGs with a β-value >0.4 with the CIMP panel were classified as CIMP high, and below or equal to 40% CIMP low (Borssen et al 2016 https://doi.org/10.1002/pbc.25958). For the Infinium MethylationEPIC (EPIC v.1) BeadChip array, 1215 CpGs were present on all three arrays. The EPIC CIMP panel was further filtered for multimapping CpGs, repeated regions, CpGs within 5 base pairs from a European SNP (Zhou, Laird, and Shen 2017 https://doi.org/10.1093/nar/gkw967), and meQTLs (Gaunt et al 2016 https://doi.org/10.1186/s13059-016-0926-z; McClay et al 2015 https://doi.org/10.1186/s13059-015-0842-7), leaving 1099 CpGs as the final EPIC v.1 CIMP panel (Roels et al 2020 https://doi.org/10.1158/2643-3230.BCD-20-0059).
To adapt the CIMP panel to the Infinium MethylationEPIC v2.0 (EPIC v.2) BeadChip, the 1099 CIMP CpGs from the EPIC v.1 array was matched by probe sequence to the EPIC v.2 manifest (Peters et al 2024 https://doi.org/10.1186/s12864-024-10027-5) with 1073 unique CpGs remaining. Duplicated EPIC v.1 probes should be aggregated to means during CIMP classification. After quality control filtering steps for the present study, 1091 CpGs in the EPIC v.1 (NOPHO) and 1028 CpGs in the EPIC v.2 (ALL10/ALL11) CIMP panels remained.

450k or EPIC v.1 array CIMP classification

If you have samples analyzed by Illumina 450k or EPIC v.1 arrays, you can used the ChAMP package pipeline in R to obtain normalized β-values and to estimate CIMP.

You can also check the ChAMP webpage for detailed info about their array analysis pipeline: https://www.bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/vignettes/ChAMP/inst/doc/ChAMP.html.

# load the ChAMP package in R
library(ChAMP)

### Set the directory with the *.idat files and a *.csv file with the columns Sample_Name, Sentrix_Position, and Sentrix_ID for each sample
setwd("C:/.../directory")

### Load array, filter probes, and obtain raw β-values
myLoad <- champ.load(directory = getwd(),
                      method="ChAMP",
                      methValue="B",
                      autoimpute=TRUE,
                      filterDetP=TRUE,
                      ProbeCutoff=0,
                      SampleCutoff=0.1,
                      detPcut=0.05,
                      filterBeads=TRUE,
                      beadCutoff=0.05,
                      filterNoCG=TRUE,
                      filterSNPs=TRUE,
                      population=NULL,
                      filterMultiHit=TRUE,
                      filterXY=TRUE,
                      force=FALSE,
                      arraytype="EPIC")  # 'EPIC' or '450k'

### Normalize the β-values using the BMIQ method   
ChampNorm <- champ.norm(beta=myLoad$beta,
                          rgSet=myLoad$rgSet,
                          mset=myLoad$mset,
                          resultsDir="./CHAMP_Normalization/",
                          method="BMIQ",
                          plotBMIQ=TRUE,
                          arraytype="EPIC") # 'EPIC' or '450k'

### Function to obtain CIMP classes and CIMP percentage for each sample using 450k or EPIC v.1 arrays
cimpClass <- function(beta, cimp)
{
    # Match data with CIMP panel
    mid <- match(cimp[,1], rownames(beta))
    cimpData <- beta[mid,]
    # Calculate CIMP percentage and CIMP class
    cimpd <- data.frame(name=colnames(cimpData),perc.meth = colMeans(cimpData>0.4, na.rm=T), stringsAsFactors=F)
    cimpd$cimp_class <- "low"
    cimpd$cimp_class[cimpd$perc.meth>0.4] <- "high"
    cimpd$perc.meth <- cimpd$perc.meth*100

return(cimpd)
}

### Get CIMP list of CpGs *.txt file from 450k or EPIC v.1 directly from from our github <>

### Obtain CIMP class and CIMP percentage for each sample
# 450k array
cimp450<- read.table("cimp450K 1293.txt", sep="\t", head=TRUE)
cimp_data <- cimpClass(ChampNorm, cimp450)
# or
# EPIC v.1 array
cimpEpic <- read.table("cimp 1099 region.txt", sep="\t", head=TRUE)
cimp_data <- cimpClass(ChampNorm, cimpEpic)

EPIC v.2 array CIMP classification

If you have samples analyzed by Illumina EPIC v.2 arrays, the SeSAMe package pipeline in R is currently indicated to obtain normalized β-values and to estimate CIMP.

You can also check the SeSAMe webpage for detailed info about their array analysis pipeline: https://www.bioconductor.org/packages/release/bioc/vignettes/sesame/inst/doc/sesame.html.

# Load the SeSAMe package in R
library(sesame)

### Make list of path and names of *.idat files (from sampleSheet)
targets <- read.table("c:\...\sampleSheet.csv", sep=",", head=T)
targets$fnames <- paste(targets$Sentrix_ID, targets$Sentrix_Position, sep="_")
targets$Basename <- paste(targets$Sentrix_ID, "/", targets$fnames, sep="")

# Import and normalize data with default prep ("QCDPB")
# Recommended QC
beta <- openSesame(targets$Basename)
colnames(beta) <- targets$Samples_Name

### Function for  CIMP classification EPIC v.2 
cimpClassEv2 <- function(beta, cimpE2)
{
# Match data with CIMP panel
    mid <- match(rownames(cimpE2), rownames(beta))

# Calculate mean of duplicated EPIC v.2 CpGs
    cimpData <- aggregate(beta[rownames(cimpE2[mid>0,]),], list(cimpE2[mid>0,"EPICv1seqmatch"]), mean, na.rm=T)
    rownames(cimpData) <- cimpData[,1]
    cimpData <- cimpData[,-1]

# Calculate CIMP percentage and CIMP class
    cimpd <- data.frame(name=colnames(beta),perc.meth = colMeans(cimpData>0.4, na.rm=T), stringsAsFactors=F)
    cimpd$cimp_class <- "low"
    cimpd$cimp_class[cimpd$perc.meth>0.4] <- "high"
    cimpd$perc.meth <- cimpd$perc.meth*100

    return(cimpd)
}
### Get CIMP list of CpGs *.txt file from EPIC v.2 directly from from our github <>

### Obtain CIMP class and CIMP percentage for each sample
cimpEpicv2 <- read.table("cimp epicv2 1073.txt", sep="\t", head=TRUE)
cimp_data <- cimpClassEv2(beta, cimpEpicv2 )
